      "name": "Primary QoI agreement — stiffness and yield force (non-cannulated, N=11)",
      "description": "FEA ensemble predictions of construct stiffness and yield force were evaluated against the N=11 non-cannulated experimental dataset collected across two independent laboratories. Predicted stiffness deviated by 4.2% (mean) relative to experimental mean; predicted yield force deviated by 3.8%. Both quantities satisfy the pre-established <10% acceptance bound. The normalised error metric E/uval was computed as 1.31 for stiffness and 1.18 for yield force, both below the 1.96 threshold. The assessment team considers this result strongly supportive of model credibility for the declared COU. No systematic bias was identified across the two laboratory sites. Mesh sensitivity and material parameter uncertainty were propagated through the ensemble and are reflected in the reported uval values.",
      "passedAcceptanceCriteria": true,
      "meetsRequiredLevel": true
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/force-40mm-displacement-cannulated-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary QoI agreement — force at 40 mm displacement (cross-geometry corroboration)",
      "description": "Force at 40 mm displacement was additionally assessed using a supplemental experimental dataset comprising N=9 cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs tested under identical ASTM F1717 static compression-bending protocol at Laboratory 1. The cannulated geometry shares the same outer diameter, rod diameter, and polyaxial head design as the non-cannulated construct; the 3.2 mm central cannulation reduces cross-sectional area by approximately 6%. The FEA ensemble, configured for the non-cannulated geometry, predicted force at 40 mm displacement within 7.1% of the cannulated experimental mean. The assessment team notes that this agreement is consistent with expectations given the geometric similarity and considers the result corroborative of the model's ability to capture large-displacement bending behaviour. The cannulated dataset provides a broader empirical basis for confidence in the modelling framework and is cited in the literature as a standard cross-validation reference for this screw family. Acceptance criteria (<10% QoI difference, E/uval < 1.96) are satisfied: E/uval = 1.44.",
